pe":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["datetime.datetime(2015, 7, 4, 0, 0)"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":155}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Pandas Time Series Data Structures"],"metadata":{"id":"bgStW7w9z0zo"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["This section will introduce the fundamental Pandas data structures for working with time series data:\n","\n","For time stamps, Pandas provides the Timestamp type. As mentioned before, it is essentially a replacement for Python's native datetime, but is based on the more efficient numpy.datetime64 data type. The associated Index structure is DatetimeIndex.\n","For time Periods, Pandas provides the Period type. This encodes a fixed-frequency interval based on numpy.datetime64. The associated index structure is PeriodIndex.\n","For time deltas or durations, Pandas provides the Timedelta type. Timedelta is a more efficient replacement for Python's native datetime.timedelta type, and is based on numpy.timedelta64. The associated index structure is TimedeltaIndex.\n","The most fundamental of these date/time objects are the Timestamp and DatetimeIndex objects. While these class objects can be invoked directly, it is more common to use the pd.to_datetime() function, which can parse a wide variety of formats. Passing a single date to pd.to_datetime() yields a Timestamp; passing a series of dates by default yields a DatetimeIndex:"],"metadata":{"id":"XyNuzofBz5_Y"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["dates = pd.to_datetime([datetime(2015, 7, 3), '4th of July, 2015',\n","                       '2015-Jul-6', '07-07-2015', '20150708'])\n","dates"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":0},"id":"exmdJW9gz7qX","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771335314138,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":18,"user":{"displayName":"kamble sahil","userId":"09120746576668669659"}},"outputId":"0796b2e2-d59c-458d-d2cb-e8d237854296"},"execution_count":156,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["DatetimeIndex(['2015-07-03', '2015-07-04', '2015-07-06', '2015-07-07',\n","               '2015-07-08'],\n","              dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq=None)"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":156}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["dates.to_period('D')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":0},"id":"XPmQfGXs0BtJ","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771335330166,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":45,"user":{"displayName":"kamble sahil","userId":"09120746576668669659"}},"outputId":"0d4409a2-7c77-485f-de56-e03d840cb0dc"},"execution_count":157,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["PeriodIndex(['2015-07-03', '2015-07-04', '2015-07-06', '2015-07-07',\n","             '2015-07-08'],\n","            dtype='period[D]')"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":157}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["dates - dates[0]"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":0},"id":"PQ4TR5tj0F5o","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771335346234,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":46,"user":{"displayName":"kamble sahil","userId":"09120746576668669659"}},"outputId":"142d3a7c-d1ba-496c-8de5-e83ae7d22f34"},"execution_count":158,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["TimedeltaIndex(['0 days', '1 days', '3 days', '4 days', '5 days'], dtype='timedelta64[ns]', freq=None)"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":158}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["pd.date_range('2015-07-03', '2015-07-10')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":0},"id":"3o7AlfWZ0J8g","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771335362743,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":48,"user":{"displayName":"kamble sahil","userId":"09120746576668669659"}},"outputId":"21cdf406-e26e-481d-cac0-d85b191a6657"},"execution_count":159,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["DatetimeIndex(['2015-07-03', '2015-07-04', '2015-07-05', '2015-07-06',\n","               '2015-07-07', '2015-07-08', '2015-07-09', '2015-07-10'],\n","              dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq='D')"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":159}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["pd.date_range('2015-07-03', periods=8)"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":0},"id":"O0dYUI7L0NM2","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771335376328,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":40,"user":{"displayName":"kamble sahil","userId":"09120746576668669659"}},"outputId":"181ee06d-d767-489a-ad23-24364bd80695"},"execution_count":160,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["DatetimeIndex(['2015-07-03', '2015-07-04', '2015-07-05', '2015-07-06',\n","               '2015-07-07', '2015-07-08', '2015-07-09', '2015-07-10'],\n","              dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq='D')"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":160}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["pd.date_range('2015-07-03', periods=8, freq='H')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":0},"id":"h3g95Ydb0RzF","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771335398945,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":53,"user":{"displayName":"kamble sahil","userId":"09120746576668669659"}},"outputId":"267e136a-33b8-44bc-a46a-c4bad84247c8"},"execution_count":161,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stderr","text":["/tmp/ipython-input-3521404607.py:1: FutureWarning: 'H' is deprecated and will be removed in a future version, please use 'h' instead.\n","  pd.date_range('2015-07-03', periods=8, freq='H')\n"]},{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["DatetimeIndex(['2015-07-03 00:00:00', '2015-07-03 01:00:00',\n","               '2015-07-03 02:00:00', '2015-07-03 03:00:00',\n","               '2015-07-03 04:00:00', '2015-07-03 05:00:00',\n","               '2015-07-03 06:00:00', '2015-07-03 07:00:00'],\n","              dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq='h')"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":161}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["pd.period_range('2015-07', periods=8, freq='M')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":0},"id":"l7fL2gzP0WjO","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771335433810,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":34,"user":{"displayName":"kamble sahil","userId":"09120746576668669659"}},"outputId":"77488705-e5c7-4dd8-a89b-67b3305f9313"},"execution_count":162,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["PeriodIndex(['2015-07', '2015-08', '2015-09', '2015-10', '2015-11', '2015-12',\n","             '2016-01', '2016-02'],\n","            dtype='period[M]')"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":162}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["pd.timedelta_range(0, periods=10, freq='H')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":0},"id":"0YbIoUrM0jSn","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771335472815,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":41,"user":{"displayName":"kamble sahil","userId":"09120746576668669659"}},"outputId":"9823eb25-28a1-4c9f-b935-9f3a6f9d6cab"},"execution_count":163,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stderr","text":["/tmp/ipython-input-3928887474.py:1: FutureWarning: 'H' is deprecated and will be removed in a future version, please use 'h' instead.\n","  pd.timedelta_range(0, periods=10, freq='H')\n"]},{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["TimedeltaIndex(['0 days 00:00:00', '0 days 01:00:00', '0 days 02:00:00',\n","                '0 days 03:00:00', '0 days 04:00:00', '0 days 05:00:00',\n","                '0 days 06:00:00', '0 days 07:00:00', '0 days 08:00:00',\n","                '0 days 09:00:00'],\n","               dtype='timedelta64[ns]', freq='h')"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":163}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Frequencies and Offsets"],"metadata":{"id":"id1i4G2d0n45"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Fundamental to these Pandas time series tools is the concept of a frequency or date offset. Just as we saw the D (day) and H (hour) codes above, we can use such codes to specify any desired frequency spacing. The following table summarizes the main codes available:"],"metadata":{"id":"SEsj_Mwe0scG"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Resampling, Shifting, and Windowing"],"metadata":{"id":"-9PAGXwS0xCU"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["The ability to use dates and times as indices to intuitively organize and access data is an important piece of the Pandas time series tools. The benefits of indexed data in general (automatic alignment during operations, intuitive data slicing and access, etc.) still apply, and Pandas provides several additional time series-specific operations.\n","\n","We will take a look at a few of those here, using some stock price data as an example. Because Pandas was developed largely in a finance context, it includes some very specific tools for financial data. For example, the accompanying pandas-datareader package (installable via conda install pandas-datareader), knows how to import financial data from a number of available sources, including Yahoo finance, Google Finance, and others. Here we will load Google's closing price history:"],"metadata":{"id":"3XfllbNt0xnC"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Q1. What is role of isnull, notnull functions in data preprocessing ?**\n","\n","ans Role of isnull() and notnull() in Data Preprocessing\n","In real-world datasets, we often have missing values (NaN).\n","\n","Examples of missing data:\n","\n","Empty cell\n","\n","NULL\n","\n","NaN\n","\n","None\n","\n","To handle them properly, we first need to detect them.\n","\n","That’s where:\n","\n","isnull()\n","\n","notnull()\n","\n","isnull()\n"," Detects missing values.\n"," True → if value is missing\n","\n","False → if value is present\n","example\n","import pandas as pd\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","df = pd.DataFrame({\n","    'A': [1, 2, np.nan],\n","    'B': [4, np.nan, 6]\n","})\n","\n","print(df.isnull())\n","notnull()\n","Detects non-missing values.\n","True → if value is NOT missing\n","\n","False → if value is missing\n","print(df.notnull())\n","df.isnull().sum()\n","df.dropna()\n","df.fillna(0)\n","df[df['A'].isnull()]\n"],"metadata":{"id":"bBbLfPCI1R-a"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**2:-  When will you use fillna method in data preprocessing step?**\n","\n","ans :- We use fillna() when a dataset contains missing values (NaN) and we want to replace them instead of deleting them.\n","Main Purpose of fillna()\n","\n","To handle missing data without losing important rows or columns.\n","When Should You Use fillna()?\n","When Missing Values Are Small in Number\n","\n","If only a few values are missing, we can replace them instead of deleting the whole row\n","example\n","df.fillna(0)\n","When Deleting Data May Cause Data Loss\n","If the dataset is small and removing rows will reduce important information.\n","df.dropna()\n","When Using Machine Learning Algorithms\n","Most ML algorithms cannot handle NaN values.\n","\n","So before training a model, we must replace missing values.\n","\n","Example:\n","df['Age'].fillna(df['Age'].mean(), inplace=True)\n","When Replacing With Statistical Values\n","\n","Common replacements:\n","\n","Type\tReplacement\n","Numeric\tMean / Median\n","Categorical\tMode\n","Time Series\tForward fill / Backward fill\n","df.fillna(df.mean())          # replace with mean\n","df.fillna(method='ffill')    # forward fill\n","df.fillna(method='bfill')    # backward fill\n"],"metadata":{"id":"GT9J7HHL2QKf"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["** 3:- What does parameter inplace=True means ?**\n","\n","ans :- The parameter inplace=True in pandas is used to modify the original DataFrame or Series directly without creating a new copy of the data. By default, most pandas functions return a new modified object and do not change the original dataset. However, when we set inplace=True, the changes are applied permanently to the existing object.\n","\n","In other words, inplace=True saves memory by avoiding the creation of a duplicate DataFrame and eliminates the need to reassign the result to the original variable.\n","\n","For example:\n","\n","df.dropna(inplace=True)\n","In this case, the missing values are removed directly from the original DataFrame df.\n","\n","If we do not use inplace=True, we must assign the result back to the variable:\n","\n","df = df.dropna()\n","Thus, inplace=True makes the operation simpler and modifies the original data structure.\n","\n","In data preprocessing, inplace=True is commonly used with functions like:\n","\n","dropna()\n","\n","fillna()\n","\n","rename()\n","\n","replace()\n","\n","sort_values()\n","\n","Therefore, inplace=True is important when we want to permanently apply changes to the dataset during data cleaning and preprocessing."],"metadata":{"id":"ihMoS6Bj29Zx"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Q4. Name and Explain any three values that method parameter may have in fillna method.**\n","ans :- The fillna() method in pandas is used to replace missing (NaN) values in a dataset. The value parameter in the fillna() method specifies what value should be used to fill the missing data. It can take different types of values depending on the requirement.\n","\n","Any three values that the value parameter may have are:\n","1. Constant Value (Scalar Value)\n","\n","We can replace missing values with a fixed constant such as 0, -1, or any specific number or string.\n","\n","Example:\n","\n","df.fillna(0)\n","\n","\n","Here, all missing values are replaced with 0.\n","\n","This is commonly used when missing values should be treated as zero or a default value.\n","2. Mean, Median, or Mode (Statistical Value)\n","\n","Missing values can be replaced with statistical measures of the column such as mean, median, or mode.\n","\n","Example:\n","\n","df.fillna(df.mean())\n","\n","\n","This replaces missing values with the mean of each column.\n","It is useful in numerical datasets to maintain data consistency.\n","3. Dictionary (Column-wise Replacement)\n","\n","We can provide a dictionary to specify different replacement values for different columns.\n","\n","Example:\n","\n","df.fillna({'Age': 25, 'Salary': 5000})\n","\n","\n","Here, missing values in the “Age” column are replaced with 25, and in the “Salary” column with 5000.\n","\n","This method is useful when different columns require different replacement values."],"metadata":{"id":"47RmdSZp3ZgQ"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Q5. Create a excel file containing 4 real numeric columns latitude, longitude, avg_temp, avg_humidity. Added manually 30 reocords and save file as weather.csv Upload this to your google drive and load it into a python variable weather_info. Show all statistical properties of the columns in this data set.**\n","\n","ans :- Step 1: Create weather.csv File\n","\n","Create an Excel file with 4 numeric columns:\n","\n","latitude\n","\n","longitude\n","\n","avg_temp\n","\n","avg_humidity\n","\n","Add 30 manually entered records like:\n","latitude,longitude,avg_temp,avg_humidity\n","18.52,73.85,30,65\n","19.07,72.87,32,70\n","28.61,77.20,35,60\n","12.97,77.59,29,75\n","22.57,88.36,33,80\n","...\n","weather.csv\n","Step 2: Load File from Google Drive into Python\n","\n","In Google Colab:\n","\n","from google.colab import drive\n","drive.mount('/content/drive')\n","Load the dataset:\n","import pandas as pd\n","\n","weather_info = pd.read_csv('/content/drive/MyDrive/weather.csv')\n","\n","weather_info.head()\n","Now the dataset is stored in the variable weather_info.\n","Step 3: Show All Statistical Properties\n","\n","To display all statistical properties of numeric columns:\n","\n","weather_info.describe()\n","Output Explanation (Statistical Properties)\n","\n","describe() shows:\n","\n","count → Number of non-null values\n","\n","mean → Average value\n","\n","std → Standard deviation\n","\n","min → Minimum value\n","\n","25% → First quartile\n","\n","50% → Median\n","\n","75% → Third quartile\n","\n","max → Maximum value\n","weather_info.info()\n","weather_info.mean()\n","weather_info.median()\n","weather_info.std()\n","weather_info.var()\n","Conclusion"],"metadata":{"id":"12hOtG3D3z-2"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["References :"],"metadata":{"id":"8p9JopKe4Nj0"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Pandas online documentation: This is the go-to source for complete documentation of the package. While the examples in the documentation tend to be small generated datasets, the description of the options is complete and generally very useful for understanding the use of various functions.\n","\n","Python for Data Analysis Written by Wes McKinney (the original creator of Pandas), this book contains much more detail on the Pandas package than we had room for in this chapter. In particular, he takes a deep dive into tools for time series, which were his bread and butter as a financial consultant. The book also has many entertaining examples of applying Pandas to gain insight from real-world datasets. Keep in mind, though, that the book is now several years old, and the Pandas package has quite a few new features that this book does not cover (but be on the lookout for a new edition in 2017).\n","\n","Stack Overflow: Pandas has so many users that any question you have has likely been asked and answered on Stack Overflow. Using Pandas is a case where some Google-Fu is your best friend. Simply go to your favorite search engine and type in the question, problem, or error you're coming across–more than likely you'll find your answer on a Stack Overflow page.\n","\n","Pandas on PyVideo: From PyCon to SciPy to PyData, many conferences have featured tutorials from Pandas developers and power users. The PyCon tutorials in particular tend to be given by very well-vetted presenters."],"metadata":{"id":"BDhEg4KC4Otn"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Conclusion : Thus we have learned how to perform Data Manipulation using Pandas Library"],"metadata":{"id":"aQbOz9lO4Rug"}}]}